Hi,

We&#39;re having trouble with JUnit 4 which appears to be due to a small change
that was made in to BaseTestRunner. The problem is a ClassCastException in
BaseTestRunner when loading our suite class. In JUnit 3, it didn&#39;t matter
what type of class was loaded as long as it had a static suite() method with
no arguments. But now in JUnit 4, the class must extend TestCase. I don&#39;t
understand why this is necessary - the getTest() method returns the Test
interface and internally it still uses reflection to get the static suite()
method.
So why does the code cast the Class to a TestCase? It seems like this is a
case of overzealous use of the new parameterized types in Java 5 and a
regression from JUnit 3.

Also, in JUnit 3 the method loadSuiteClass() called getLoader() to get the
ClassLoader to use, which opened the door for extensibility. This is gone
now, why?

Thanks in advance...
